net.frozencode.jniolib.server

Class JNioServer

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.frozencode.jniolib.server.JNioServer

  • public final class JNioServer
extends java.lang.Object
    The JNioServer class coordinates the accepting of, reading from, writing to, and disconnecting of clients. A JNioServer delegates the task of responding to these occurrences to JNioEventListener objects. Implementation notes: A JNioServer object uses a thread during normal operation for network reads/writes. This thread is not started until after the first call to one of the bindListeningAddress() methods is made. The thread is only stopped after a call to shutdown() is made. This class is thread-safe.

      • shutdown

        public void shutdown()
        Asynchronously instructs the JNioServer to cleanly shut down, disconnecting all clients. If the JNioServer was already shut down, this method does nothing. If it is required that the JNioServer be completely shut down before execution can continue, the join() method of JNioServer may be used to block until the server has shut down.

      • isShutdown

        public boolean isShutdown()
        Returns true if the shutdown() method for this JNioServer has been called. Note that, even if this method returns true, the server may not have *finished* shutting down. To determine if the server has completed the shutdown process, use this method in conjunction with the isAlive() method, like so: srv.isShutdown() && !srv.isAlive(). Alternatively, the server's join() method may be used to block until the server has finished shutting down.
        Returns:
        true if the shutdown() method for this JNioServer has been called, false otherwise.

      • isAlive

        public boolean isAlive()
        Tests if this JNioServer is alive. A thread is alive if it has been started and has not yet shut down.
        Returns:
        true if this JNioServer is alive; false otherwise.
